msgid "Summary"
msgstr ""

#: ../../_sources/Recursion/Summary.rst:8
msgid ""
"In this chapter we have looked at examples of several recursive "
"algorithms. These algorithms were chosen to expose you to several "
"different problems where recursion is an effective problem-solving "
"technique. The key points to remember from this chapter are as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../_sources/Recursion/Summary.rst:13
msgid "All recursive algorithms must have a base case."
msgstr ""

#: ../../_sources/Recursion/Summary.rst:15
msgid ""
"A recursive algorithm must change its state and make progress toward the "
"base case."
msgstr ""

#: ../../_sources/Recursion/Summary.rst:18
msgid "A recursive algorithm must call itself (recursively)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../_sources/Recursion/Summary.rst:20
msgid "Recursion can take the place of iteration in some cases."
msgstr ""

#: ../../_sources/Recursion/Summary.rst:22
msgid ""
"Recursive algorithms often map very naturally to a formal expression of "
"the problem you are trying to solve."
msgstr ""

#: ../../_sources/Recursion/Summary.rst:25
msgid ""
"Recursion is not always the answer. Sometimes a recursive solution may be"
" more computationally expensive than an alternative algorithm."
msgstr ""

